subjectkey: The NDAR Global Unique Identifier (GUID) for research subject
interview_date: Date on which the interview/genetic test/sampling/imaging/biospecimen was completed. MM/DD/YYYY
study: Study; The code for each individual study
mcg_ao_blow: Blow to indicate something is hot
mcg_ao_drink: Drink from a cup containing liquid
mcg_ao_eat: Eat with a spoon or fork
mcg_ao_head: Lay head on hands and squeeze eyes shut as if sleeping
mcg_ao_neck: Put on a necklace, bracelet, or watch
mcg_ao_plane: Hold plane and make it fly""
mcg_ao_pour: Pour pretend liquid from one container to another
mcg_ao_shoe: Put on a shoe or sock
mcg_ao_stir: Stir pretend liquid in a cup or pan with a spoon
mcg_ao_wipe: Wipe face or hands with a towel or cloth
mcg_cg_arms: Extends arm to show you something he/she is holding
mcg_cg_extends: Extends his/her arm upward to signal a wish to be picked up
mcg_cg_hush: Gestures hush" by pacing finger to lips"
mcg_cg_lips: Smacks lips in yum yum" gesture to indicate that something taste good"
mcg_cg_point: Points (with arm and index finger extended) at some interesting object or event
mcg_cg_reach: Reaches out and gives you a toy or some object that he/she is holding
mcg_cg_request: Requests something by extending arm and opening and closing hand
mcg_cg_shrugs: Shrugs to indicate all gone" or "where'd it go""
mcg_cg_total: Total number of first communicative gestures
mcg_cg_waves: Waves bye-bye on his/her own when someone leaves
mcg_eg_ageeq: MacArthur Words and Gestures: Early Gestures - Age Equivalent
mcg_lg_ageeq: MacArthur Words and Gestures: Later Gestures - Age Equivalent
mcg_gr_total: Total number of games and routines
mcg_ia_drive: Drive car by turning steering wheel
mcg_ia_key: Put key in door or lock
mcg_ia_type: Type at a typewriter or computer keyboard
mcg_ia_write: Write with pen, pencil, or marker
mcg_ph_ageeq: MacArthur Words and Gestures: Phrases - Age Equivalent
mcg_su_total: MacArthur Words and Gestures: First signs of understanding - Total
mcg_ph_ride: Want to go for a ride? Understands?
mcg_ph_time: Time to go night night. Understands?
mcg_po_example: If yes (to above), please give several examples
mcg_po_replace: During play, children sometimes use an object as a replacement for another.
mcg_pp_diaper: Try to put diaper on it
mcg_pp_put: Try to put show or sock or hat on it
mcg_pp_total: Total Pretending to be a parent
mcg_st_imitate: Some children like to parrot" or imitate things that they've just heard"
mcg_st_naming: Some children like to go around naming or labeling things, as though proud of knowing the names and wanting to show this. How often does your child do this?
mcg_su_md: React to there's mommy/daddy" by looking around for them"
mcg_su_name: Respond when name is called (e.g., by turning and looking as source)
mcg_su_no: Respond to no, no" (by stopping what he/she is doing at least for a moment)"
mcg_teach: MacArthur Words and Gestures: Teacher Completed Form
mcg_tg_ageeq: MacArthur Words and Gestures: Total Gestures - Age Equivalent
mcg_vc_cageeq: Total number of words understood: Age Equivalent
mcg_vc_pageeq: Total number of words produced: Age Equivalent
mcg_combine: Has your child begun to combine words yet, such as ''nother cookie'' or ''doggie bite''?
mcg_language: What language(s) do you speak in your home?
mcg_cpreflang: What is your child's preferred language?
